Shader-Based Renewable Energy Farm Visualization
=================================================

Author: Gunabhiram Aruru
Course: CSCI 4229/5229 Computer Graphics

Project Summary
---------------
This interactive OpenGL scene presents a renewable-energy farm containing
three animated wind turbines, a barn, a transparent greenhouse, a solar-panel
array, battery-storage cabinets, utility equipment, trees, fencing, a road
network, and expanded textured terrain. The default perspective view shows
the complete scene immediately with lighting, textures, fog,
greenhouse glass, wind ribbons, turbine animation, and the moving light
enabled.

My original contribution is a GLSL-animated wind-flow visualization whose speed is interactively coupled to the physical animation of all wind turbines.

Build and Run
-------------
Run from the project directory:

    make clean
    make
    ./final

The Makefile uses:

    g++ -std=c++11 -Wall -Wextra

Linux systems may optionally build with GLEW by running `make USEGLEW=1`.

Controls
--------

    0                 Full-scene inspection view
    1                 Inspect wind turbine
    2                 Inspect solar panel
    3                 Inspect battery-storage cabinet
    4                 Inspect substation
    5                 Inspect greenhouse
    6                 Inspect barn/control building
    7                 Inspect weather station
    8                 Inspect sheep
    9                 Inspect farmer
    Arrow keys        Rotate overview camera; turn/move in first person
    PageUp/PageDown   Zoom in/out or decrease/increase field of view
    + or =            Zoom in / decrease field of view
    - or _            Zoom out / increase field of view
    m                 Cycle orthographic, perspective, and first-person views
    R                 Reset to the default full-scene perspective view
    r                 Pause/resume turbine blades
    a                 Toggle coordinate axes
    l                 Toggle lighting
    f or F            Toggle distance fog
    t                 Toggle textures
    g                 Toggle greenhouse glass
    s or S            Toggle animated wind-flow ribbons
    Space             Pause/resume automatic light movement
    , and .           Move the light angle manually
    [ and ]           Decrease/increase wind speed
    < and >           Lower/raise the light
    q, Q, or ESC      Exit cleanly

Feature List
------------
- Handmade reusable geometry for turbines, buildings, greenhouse framing,
  solar panels, battery cabinets, trees, fences, expanded terrain, and paths
- Three instanced turbines with frame-rate-independent rotor animation
- Nine instanced solar panels with raised frames, supports, and reflective faces
- Shared interactive wind speed from 0.0 to 5.0
- Twelve translucent wind-flow ribbons animated by GLSL
- Fixed-pipeline ribbon fallback if GLSL loading or compilation fails
- Transparent greenhouse walls and roof
- Textured terrain, metal, wood, roof, and path surfaces
- Moving positional light and material-specific specular response
- Toggleable linear distance fog
- Perspective, orthographic, and first-person cameras
- Six object-inspection presets and a screen-space status HUD

Wind-Speed Model
----------------
Wind speed is a shared simulation value. Turbine angular speed is:

    blade degrees/second = 45 * windSpeed

At the default wind speed of 1.0, every rotor turns at 45 degrees per second,
or 7.5 RPM. The vertex shader uses the same value to control ribbon travel and
displacement, so increasing or decreasing the wind changes both visual airflow
and physical turbine motion. Elapsed wall-clock time keeps rotor animation
independent of frame rate.

Transparency, Shaders, and Fog
------------------------------
Opaque geometry is rendered first. Wind ribbons are blended afterward with
depth testing enabled and depth writes disabled. Greenhouse glass is rendered
last using source-alpha blending, also with depth testing enabled and depth
writes disabled. This preserves occlusion by solid objects while allowing the
scene and airflow behind the glazing to remain visible.

The wind vertex shader displaces ribbon vertices with time- and wind-driven
sine waves. The fragment shader blends blue and white airflow colors and
applies the same linear fog model used by fixed-pipeline scene geometry.
Shader compilation and linking errors are reported without terminating the
program.

Original Graduate Contribution
------------------------------
The original graduate-level contribution is the coupled shader visualization:
GLSL-animated airflow ribbons communicate wind direction and motion while one
interactive wind-speed value drives both shader animation and all turbine
rotors. The contribution includes shader loading, compile/link diagnostics,
uniform management, transparent render ordering, fixed-pipeline fallback, and
fog integration.

Reused HW3 Code Disclosure
--------------------------
The BMP texture loader and the original handmade farm foundation were adapted
from my HW3 work. Reused elements include the turbine model, barn, fence, path,
ground, texture mapping, fixed-pipeline lighting, camera navigation, and basic
animation structure. The working geometry for these elements was retained
rather than rewritten.

New Work Added for the Final Project
------------------------------------
- Greenhouse frame and separately rendered transparent glazing
- Angled photovoltaic array with handmade supports
- Expanded terrain with outer crop rows and revised full-scene framing
- Four handmade battery-storage cabinets in a fenced yard with vents, warning
  labels, side cable boxes, collection equipment, and substation conduits
- 90-by-90-unit farm layout divided into turbine, solar, battery, substation,
  barn, greenhouse, paddock, and connecting-road zones
- Raised textured road network with access branches and no ground z-fighting
- Functional zone fences, identification signs, utility poles, roadside
  erosion-control rocks, paddock water trough, crop rows, and tree windbreaks
- Low-poly trees and expanded secondary scenery
- Object-inspection modes with centered camera presets
- Shared wind-speed model and frame-rate-independent turbine motion
- GLSL loading, compilation, linking, diagnostics, and fallback behavior
- Twelve animated translucent wind-flow ribbons
- Coupling between shader airflow speed and turbine rotor speed
- Linear distance fog in both fixed-pipeline and shader-rendered geometry
- Final lighting/material polish and expanded HUD status reporting

Required Runtime Files
----------------------
Shader files, required in the project directory:

    wind.vert
    wind.frag

Texture files, required under `textures/`:

    textures/grass.bmp
    textures/metal.bmp
    textures/path.bmp
    textures/roof.bmp
    textures/wood.bmp

Time Spent
----------
Approximately 1 hour on the final-project additions and review passes,
excluding the earlier HW3 implementation reused as the scene foundation.

Known Limitations
-----------------
- The program uses compatibility-profile OpenGL/GLUT and GLSL 1.20.
- Greenhouse glass uses fixed-pipeline alpha blending rather than a refraction
  or physically based material.
- Transparent surfaces are ordered by object pass, not sorted per polygon.
- Asset paths are relative; run `./final` from the project directory.
- First-person movement does not perform collision detection.
